<%- include('partials/subheader-2'); %>

<div class="uk-card uk-card-secondary">
  <div class="uk-card-body">

      <h1 class="uk-card-title uk-text-uppercase uk-text-success"><b><%= pledge.country %></b></h1>
      <h4 class="uk-card-title uk-text-uppercase">pledged to achieve
        <span class="uk-text-success uk-text-bold"><%= pledge.end_target %></span> by
        <span class="uk-text-success uk-text-bold"><%= pledge.end_target_year %></span>.</h4>

      <h4 class="uk-margin uk-h4">Target Status: <span class="uk-text-uppercase uk-text-bolder"> <%= pledge.end_target_status %> </span> </h4>
      <h4 class="uk-margin uk-h4">Interim Target: <span class="uk-text-uppercase uk-text-bolder"> <%= pledge.interim_target %> by <%= pledge.interim_target_year %></span> </h4>

   </div>
</div>

<div class="uk-section uk-section-muted">
  <div class="uk-container">
    <div class="uk-child-width-1-2@s uk-grid-collapse uk-text-center uk-height-large" uk-grid>
      <div>
          <div class="uk-tile uk-tile-muted uk-height-large">
              <p></p>
              <p></p>
              <h2 class="uk-text-bold uk-text-large">What do these targets mean?</h2>
              <span uk-icon="icon: arrow-right; ratio:5"></span>
          </div>
      </div>
      <div>
          <div class="uk-tile uk-tile-muted uk-height-large">
            <div class="uk-width-4-5@m uk-margin-auto uk-button-group uk-align-center">
              <ul class="uk-subnav uk-subnav-pill" uk-switcher>
                  <li><a href="#">1.5 target</a></li>
                  <li><a href="#">Carbon neutrality</a></li>
                  <li><a href="#">Climate neutrality</a></li>
                  <li><a href="#">Absolute emissions target</a></li>
                  <li><a href="#">Emissions intensity target</a></li>
                  <li><a href="#">Emissions reduction target</a></li>
                  <li><a href="#">GHG neutrality</a></li>
                  <li><a href="#">Net zero</a></li>
                  <li><a href="#">Reduction against Business as Usual (BAU)</a></li>
                  <li><a href="#">Zero carbon</a></li>
              </ul>
              
              <ul class="uk-switcher uk-margin">
                  <li>A commitment to limiting global warming to 1.5 degrees</li>
                  <li>Zero net human-caused CO2 emissions by a certain date. CO2 emissions are balanced so that they are equal or less than the CO2 removed through the planet's natural absorption.</li>
                  <li>The concept is very similar to carbon neutrality but it extends to all GHG emissions.</li>
                  <li>No matter what the present level of emissions is, absolute emissions targets specify the quantity of emissions to strive for by a specific year or time period. For instance, "X will limit emissions to no more than 10 million tonnes of CO2 equivalent in 2025."</li>
                  <li>A target for emissions in relation to a non-emissions unit, such as per unit of output or per unit of GDP. For instance, "X will reduce the amount of CO2 emissions produced per unit of GDP by 18% over the period of 2021 to 2025."</li>
                  <li>Bring annual GHG emissions down by a target year in comparison to a historical baseline year; for instance, "X will bring its GHG emissions down by 50% below 1990 levels by 2030."</li>
                  <li>The concept is similar to climate neutrality but it only refers to GHG emissions and excludes geoengineering.</li>
                  <li>The concept is similar to carbon neutrality, but it covers all GHG emissions and does not permit compensated emissions (e.g. via offsets). It requires abatement of emissions.</li>
                  <li>Specifies a reduction compared with a baseline of what emissions were projected to have been at a certain date, for example "X will reduce emissions 29% below business-as-usual by 2030."</li>
                  <li>No carbon emissions are being produced from a product or service.</li>
              </ul>
            
          </div>
          </div>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
</div>



